english:
  title: A Letter of Gratitude to the Spirits
  author: Jung Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the region of Hoejin, great mountains rise with dense forests, nestled near the sea where no human dwellings stand. Mist and miasma swirl and transform into shadow-breath, bringing endless rain. From the mountains and sea, from the yin and void, from the essence of grass and wood, earth and stone—all mingled, fused, and transmuted—emerge the sprites and demons. They are neither human nor ghost, belonging neither to the shadowed realm nor the bright world, yet they are something real.

    The Master Jeong sat alone in his chamber, where daylight stretched long and silent. One afternoon, leaning on his staff, he ventured forth, hands clasped behind, gazing across the distant landscape. Mountains and waters twisted together, grasses and trees intertwined. Heaven and field grew dim and murky, all that met his eye tinged with melancholy. The shadowed breath seeped into his body, and his limbs grew heavy and numb. Returning to his room, he sat troubled and dazed, exhaustion overwhelming him. He reclined, head bowed, eyes closed—suspended between sleep and waking—when those very sprites began their sport: mocking, sighing, weaving back and forth on currents of air. Some seemed to dance with glee, others to weep, still others to laugh. They leapt and cavorted, then grew still and submissive, attempting to win his favor. The Master, wearied by their clamorous pestering and disturbed by their ominous presence, raised his hand to drive them away. Yet they departed only to return. Unable to bear it longer, he cried out with a great voice—and suddenly awoke. The forms vanished, the traces dissolved into emptiness. Yet his spirit trembled, his breath faltered, as though he had lost something precious. Only after a long while did he find his peace again.

    Calling his mind inward, stilling his breath, he sat in quiet repose—when the sprites returned, drawing their companions about them, gathering in multitudes as before.

    The Master spoke: "You are creatures of shadow, not of my kind. Why do you come? Why do you grieve, rejoice, and laugh?"

    When he finished, one seemed to step forward and speak thus: "In the great capitals and thriving cities, mansions line the streets and officials pass in procession—these are where human beings dwell. In dim hollows and desolate wastes, there we spirits gather. You came to us, not we to you. How can you bid us depart? You did not measure your own strength, transgressed the boundaries of custom, and were cast out from the bright court. Is this not laughable? You labored in your studies, held firm in purpose, walked a righteous path—yet in the end you were banished, with no way to vindicate yourself. Is this not sorrowful? We dwell in darkness, unknown to the world. Yet your learning runs deep, your wisdom boundless—and now you journey with us in these remote and desolate lands. Is this not cause for joy? Moreover, you cannot stand among ordinary folk; you have been sent to distant exile. Those who see you grow uneasy; those who speak with you grow fearful. All turn away their hands and avert their steps. Only we rejoice at your coming and welcome you as a companion. Now, if you reject us as being of a different kind, I ask: besides us, who will call you friend?"

    Hearing this, the Master felt shame at their words, yet was moved by their sincerity. Thus he composed this reply:

    *Upon the mountain's slope,
    in the sea's far corner,
    the heaven's breath hangs shadowed—
    grass and wood dwell in obscurity.
    Alone, without another soul,
    who else would I seek for company?
    From dawn we venture forth together,
    through the evening we abide as one.
    We sing to answer one another's call
    as spring departs and autumn comes.
    Having already turned from the world's demands,
    what more could I desire?
    Amid the wild grasses swaying,
    let us linger here in gentle joy.*
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Hoejin (會津) refers to a remote coastal region known for its mist-shrouded landscape.
  - key: ''
    value: The sprites (魑魅魍魎) represent supernatural beings born from natural essences in uninhabited places—a common motif in Chinese and Korean mystical literature.
  - key: ''
    value: This work is an allegory reflecting Jung Do-jeon's own political exile and vindication of an intellectual's worth beyond worldly recognition.
